notes.body:
Start with the friendliest family. You're standing on a grid, you may only step **right or down**, and you want the cheapest route from top-left to bottom-right. Ask each cell one question: *"who could have stepped into me?"* Only the cell **above** and the cell to the **left**. So if you already know the best cost to reach those two, the best cost to reach `(i,j)` is decided:

[[fig:m13-grid-deps]]

```cpp
// Min path sum from top-left to bottom-right (Unique Paths / Min Path Sum share this shape)
int minPathSum(vector<vector<int>>& g) {
    int m = g.size(), n = g[0].size();
    // dp[i][j] = best cost to REACH cell (i,j)
    vector<vector<int>> dp(m, vector<int>(n, 0));
    for (int i = 0; i < m; i++)
        for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
            if (i == 0 && j == 0) dp[i][j] = g[0][0];          // start
            else {
                int up   = (i > 0) ? dp[i-1][j] : INT_MAX;      // came from above
                int left = (j > 0) ? dp[i][j-1] : INT_MAX;      // came from left
                dp[i][j] = g[i][j] + min(up, left);
            }
        }
    return dp[m-1][n-1];
    // For COUNTING paths: dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j] + dp[i][j-1], base dp[0][0]=1.
    // Space: can compress to a single row (1D) since you only look up/left.
}
```

Row-major order (`for i, for j`) is exactly right here: by the time you compute `dp[i][j]`, the row above is fully done and the cell to your left in this row is done. Dependencies are always ready — no cleverness required.

> [!INTUITION]
> Don't think "explore paths forward". Think **backwards at each cell**: "the last step into me came from up or from left, so my answer is my own cost plus the better of those two finished answers." That one flip of perspective turns an exponential path search into $O(mn)$ table-filling.

> [!EXAMPLE]
> Grid `[[1,3,1],[1,5,1],[4,2,1]]`. Top row accumulates: `1,4,5`. Left column: `1,2,6`. Then `dp[1][1] = 5 + min(4,2) = 7`, `dp[1][2] = 1 + min(5,7) = 6`, `dp[2][1] = 2 + min(7,6) = 8`, `dp[2][2] = 1 + min(6,8) = 7`. Answer **7** (path 1→3→1→1→1).

> [!NOTE]
> Two knobs turn this one template into the first four ladder problems: swap `min` for `+` and you're **counting** paths (Unique Paths); an obstacle just forces `dp[i][j] = 0` (Unique Paths II); a jagged grid like Triangle is the same idea with two children instead of up/left. And since you only read the previous row, a single rolling 1D row gives $O(n)$ space.

New shape: **two** strings, and you must relate them — find their longest common subsequence, or edit one into the other. The state is a pair of prefixes: `dp[i][j]` = answer for the first `i` characters of `a` and the first `j` characters of `b`. The table is `(m+1) × (n+1)` because row 0 and column 0 represent the **empty prefix** — the free base case that makes the recurrence clean.

```cpp
// Longest Common Subsequence — the parent of edit distance, min-delete, etc.
int lcs(const string& a, const string& b) {
    int m = a.size(), n = b.size();
    // dp[i][j] = LCS of a[0..i-1] and b[0..j-1]. Row/col 0 = empty prefix = 0.
    vector<vector<int>> dp(m+1, vector<int>(n+1, 0));
    for (int i = 1; i <= m; i++)
        for (int j = 1; j <= n; j++) {
            if (a[i-1] == b[j-1])
                dp[i][j] = 1 + dp[i-1][j-1];          // match: extend diagonal
            else
                dp[i][j] = max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]); // skip one char
        }
    return dp[m][n];
}
```

The recurrence is a decision about the **last characters** of the two prefixes. If they match, they belong together in the answer: take `1 +` the diagonal (both prefixes shrink). If they don't, one of them is dead weight: drop `a`'s last char (look up) or drop `b`'s last char (look left), and keep the better result.

[[fig:m13-lcs-table]]

> [!ANALOGY]
> This table is exactly what a `diff` tool computes. Walking the grid is aligning the two strings: a diagonal move pairs two characters up, a vertical or horizontal move skips a character in one string. LCS finds the longest pairing; edit distance (deep dive below) finds the cheapest walk.

> [!PITFALL]
> The #1 bug in this family: `dp[i][j]` talks about **prefixes of length** `i` and `j`, so the characters being compared are `a[i-1]` and `b[j-1]` — not `a[i]`. Pick the `+1`-padded convention, write the comment `// dp[i][j] = answer for a[0..i-1], b[0..j-1]` at the top, and stay consistent. Mixing 0-indexed strings with 1-indexed DP silently corrupts the whole table.

> [!KEY]
> Learn the **disguises** — they turn hards into one-liners: "minimum deletions to make two strings equal" is `m + n - 2*LCS(a,b)` (Delete Operation for Two Strings), and "longest palindromic subsequence" is `LCS(s, reverse(s))`. Spotting a reduction to LCS saves you from deriving a recurrence from scratch under the clock.

Palindromes get their own mini-family because three ladder problems share one table. The observation: `s[i..j]` is a palindrome **iff** `s[i] == s[j]` *and* the inside `s[i+1..j-1]` is already a palindrome. The inner range is shorter, so this is interval DP with a boolean table — and there's a slick iteration order that avoids the explicit `len` loop:

```cpp
int countSubstrings(string s) {
    int n = s.size(), cnt = 0;
    vector<vector<bool>> dp(n, vector<bool>(n, false));
    for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--)          // i decreasing so i+1 is done
        for (int j = i; j < n; j++) {          // j increasing so j-1 is done
            if (s[i] == s[j] && (j - i < 2 || dp[i+1][j-1])) {
                dp[i][j] = true;               // len 0/1/2 need no inner check
                cnt++;
            }
        }
    return cnt;
}
```

Running `i` downward and `j` upward means `dp[i+1][j-1]` (one row below, one column left) is always finished — same guarantee as iterating by length, fewer lines.

> [!PITFALL]
> The `j - i < 2` guard is load-bearing. A single character (`j == i`) and two equal adjacent characters (`j - i == 1`) are palindromes with **no inside to check** — and `dp[i+1][j-1]` would be an inverted/out-of-range read for them. Short-circuit *before* touching the inner cell, or you'll read garbage for every length-1 and length-2 substring.

> [!NOTE]
> One table, three problems: count the `true` cells → **Palindromic Substrings**; track the max `j - i + 1` where `dp[i][j]` is true → **Longest Palindromic Substring**; switch the booleans to lengths on `[i..j]` (or just run LCS against the reverse) → **Longest Palindromic Subsequence**. All $O(n^2)$ time and space.

> [!EXAM]
> For Longest Palindromic Substring specifically, **expand-around-center** is also $O(n^2)$ time but $O(1)$ space and less code — try each of the $2n-1$ centers. In an OA, write whichever you can produce fastest without bugs; the table generalizes better, the expansion is quicker to type.

deepdives.answer:
**Naive, and why it dies.** For every cell, try every square size and verify all its cells: $O((mn)\cdot\min(m,n)^2)$. On a big matrix that times out — and it also throws away everything you learned from neighbouring cells.

> [!INTUITION]
> The whole trick is the state definition: `dp[i][j]` = **side length of the largest all-1 square whose bottom-right corner sits at `(i,j)`**. Anchoring the square at its bottom-right corner is what makes the recurrence *local* — a square ending here is just three slightly smaller squares ending at my three neighbours, plus me.

If `matrix[i][j] == 1`, a square of side `s` can end here only if squares of side `s-1` end at the cell **above**, the cell to the **left**, and the **diagonal** neighbour — those three squares tile everything except the current cell:

```cpp
if (matrix[i][j] == '1')
    dp[i][j] = 1 + min({ dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1], dp[i-1][j-1] });
else
    dp[i][j] = 0;   // a 0 cell can be no square's corner
```

**Why `min` and not `max`?** A square is only as strong as its weakest supporting corner. Suppose up allows side 3 but the diagonal only allows side 1 — then the top-left region of your would-be 4×4 has a hole, and all you can *guarantee* is a 2×2. The `min` takes the largest side that **all three** neighbours can support, and the `+1` adds the current cell.

[[fig:m13-square-min3]]

Full solution — note the `+1` border trick that deletes all the `i-1`/`j-1` boundary checks:

```cpp
int maximalSquare(vector<vector<char>>& m) {
    int R = m.size(), C = m[0].size(), best = 0;
    vector<vector<int>> dp(R+1, vector<int>(C+1, 0)); // +1 border avoids i-1/j-1 checks
    for (int i = 1; i <= R; i++)
        for (int j = 1; j <= C; j++)
            if (m[i-1][j-1] == '1') {
                dp[i][j] = 1 + min({dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1], dp[i-1][j-1]});
                best = max(best, dp[i][j]);
            }
    return best * best;
}
```

**Complexity:** time $O(mn)$, space $O(mn)$, compressible to $O(n)$ with a rolling row plus one temp for the diagonal.

> [!PITFALL]
> The problem asks for the **area**. Track the max *side* while filling, return `best * best`. Losing a test on the very last line is a rite of passage — skip it.

**What generalizes:** "anchor the shape at a corner cell and express it via neighbours" is the move behind Maximal Rectangle (per-row histograms), Count Square Submatrices, and largest-plus-sign problems.

**Naive:** enumerate all $O(n^2)$ substrings and palindrome-check each in $O(n)$ — that's $O(n^3)$, too slow and too wasteful: checking `"abcba"` re-verifies `"bcb"`, which re-verifies `"c"`.

> [!INTUITION]
> Recursion in one line: `s[i..j]` is a palindrome **iff** `s[i] == s[j]` **and** `s[i+1..j-1]` is one. The inner range is strictly shorter — so if you compute short ranges before long ones, every lookup is already answered. That's interval DP with booleans.

The elegant iteration order: run `i` from the bottom **up** and `j` from `i` **rightward**. Then `dp[i+1][j-1]` (one row below, one column earlier) is always done — no explicit length loop needed:

```cpp
int countSubstrings(string s) {
    int n = s.size(), cnt = 0;
    vector<vector<bool>> dp(n, vector<bool>(n, false));
    for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--)          // i decreasing so i+1 is done
        for (int j = i; j < n; j++) {          // j increasing so j-1 is done
            if (s[i] == s[j] && (j - i < 2 || dp[i+1][j-1])) {
                dp[i][j] = true;               // len 0/1/2 need no inner check
                cnt++;
            }
        }
    return cnt;
}
```

> [!PITFALL]
> The subtle bit is `j - i < 2`. A single character (`j == i`) and two equal adjacent characters (`j - i == 1`) are palindromes **without consulting the inner cell** — and for them `dp[i+1][j-1]` is an inverted or out-of-range read. The short-circuit `||` must fire *before* the table lookup. Move that guard after the lookup and you read garbage for every short substring.

**Complexity:** time and space $O(n^2)$.

**What generalizes:** this exact table, unchanged, answers **Longest Palindromic Substring** (track the max `j - i + 1` over true cells) — and its "lengths instead of booleans" cousin is Longest Palindromic Subsequence. One table, three ladder problems.
